SIMPLE: twin
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Twin
<hw>Twin</hw> <pr>(tw⟦icr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>twin</ets> double, AS. <ets>getwinne</ets> two and two, pl., twins;
akin to D. <ets>tweeling</ets> a twin, G. <ets>zwilling</ets>, OHG.
<ets>zwiniling</ets>, Icel. <ets>tvennr</ets>, <ets>tvinnr</ets>, two
and two, twin, and to AS. <ets>twi-</ets> two. See <er>Twice</er>,
<er>Two</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being one of two born at a birth;
<as>as, a <ex>twin</ex> brother or sister</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Being one of a pair much resembling one another;
standing in the relation of a twin to something else; -- often followed
by <xex>to</xex> or <xex>with</xex>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Double; consisting of two similar
and corresponding parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>Composed of parts united
according to some definite law of twinning. See <er>Twin</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Twin boat</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Twin
ship</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a vessel whose deck and
upper works rest on two parallel hulls.</cd> -- <col><b>Twin
crystal</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Twin</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 4.</cd> --
<col><b>Twin flower</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a delicate
evergreen plant (<spn>Linnaea borealis</spn>) of northern climates,
which has pretty, fragrant, pendulous flowers borne in pairs on a
slender stalk.</cd> -- <col><b>Twin-screw steamer</b></col>, <cd>a steam
vessel propelled by two screws, one on either side of the plane of the
keel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Twin
<hw>Twin</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of two produced at a
birth, especially by an animal that ordinarily brings forth but one at a
birth; -- used chiefly in the plural, and applied to the young of beasts
as well as to human young.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A sign and
constellation of the zodiac; Gemini. See <er>Gemini</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person or thing that closely resembles
another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>A compound crystal composed
of two or more crystals, or parts of crystals, in reversed position with
reference to each other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The relative position of the parts of a twin may be
explained by supposing one part to be revolved 180⟦deg⟧ about a certain
axis (called the <xex>twinning axis</xex>), this axis being normal to a
plane (called the <xex>twinning plane</xex>) which is usually one of the
fundamental planes of the crystal. This revolution brings the two parts
into parallel position, or vice versa. A <xex>contact twin</xex> is one
in which the parts are united by a plane surface, called the
<xex>composition face</xex>, which is usually the same as the twinning
plane. A <xex>penetration twin</xex> is one in which the parts
interpenetrate each other, often very irregularly. Twins are also
called, according to form, <xex>cruciform</xex>, <xex>geniculated</xex>,
etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Twin
<hw>Twin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Twinned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Twinning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring forth
twins.</def> <rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be born at the same birth.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Twin
<hw>Twin</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to be twins,
or like twins in any way.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Still we moved⟦br⟧
Together, <qex>twinned</qex>, as horse's ear and eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To separate into two parts; to part; to divide;
hence, to remove; also, to strip; to rob.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The life out of her body for to <qex>twin</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Twin
<hw>Twin</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To depart from a place or
thing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Ere that we farther
<xex>twin</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twinborn</ent>⟦br⟧
